# Film & Media Five-Day Market

### An Essay Toward a Post-Political Communal Space

## Prologue

### Before the Plaza — Why I Am Writing This Book

The plazas of Korea are opening again.
As elections approach, people pour into the streets, and the squares fill with voices. Cameras roll, slogans echo, and people say it feels almost like a festival. Inside that phrase is a peculiar emotional mixture: excitement, anticipation, even a premonition of victory. Bodies loosen. Strangers speak to one another with ease. Personal fatigue dissolves, if only briefly, into collective heat. For a long time, we called that sensation liberation.

Yet whenever I stand before such plazas, I find myself hesitating. I can feel the heat, but I sense that I am searching for something else. Perhaps because I once experienced a far more intense collective feeling in a place much smaller and more fragile — while making village films.

Someone forgot their lines. Someone else felt embarrassed simply seeing their own face projected on a screen. These scenes were far removed from polished art, yet they left me with a strange shock. There were no winners or losers there, no hierarchy. People were merely offering fragments of their own time to one another.

This book begins with that question.
Why, in an age when political plazas grow larger and more spectacular, do we find ourselves longing instead for smaller, slower, imperfect spaces? To whom does the plaza belong? How are crowds formed, what do they gain, and what do they lose? And can film, media, or temporary communal spaces like the old Korean five-day markets — appearing briefly and disappearing again — offer us another possibility?

These questions will be explored not through academic argument but through the form of the essay. I will refer to theory without becoming trapped inside it. I will begin from personal experience without remaining confined there. A book that slowly crosses the plaza together with the reader — perhaps that is what this work hopes to become.

