## Chapter 2

### Three Types of Crowds — Politics, Sports, Art

Though gathered in the same space, they exist there in entirely different ways.

### Political Crowds: Heat Organized Toward Purpose

The defining feature of political crowds is purpose. People gather to change something, or to defend something. That shared objective becomes the axis that binds the crowd together.

This is why slogans matter in political rallies. A slogan is not merely sound; it is a ritual repeatedly reaffirming collective purpose.

Political crowds also generate hierarchy. Those on stage and those below it. Those holding microphones and those clapping. Those seen and those anonymous. Even in democratic plazas, this hierarchy functions structurally. Out of it emerges the figure of “the representative” — the one who speaks on behalf of the crowd.

Political crowds feel intense because they carry the weight of history. *We are making history.* In that moment, ordinary existence seems elevated into historical existence.

Yet this elevation also contains danger. The consciousness of being “history’s subject” can make ordinary life outside the plaza seem unbearably small, even meaningless.

### Sports Crowds: Bodies Riding Shared Victory and Defeat

Unlike political crowds, sports crowds are less about change than about shared experience itself.

The 2002 World Cup street gatherings in Korea revealed the overwhelming power of collective sports catharsis. At every victory, bodies flooded into the streets. Strangers embraced one another. Nation, team colors, chants — all temporarily overwhelmed individual identity.

It was one of the rare forms of collective ecstasy still permitted within modern society.

Yet sports crowds depend fundamentally upon outcome. The community lasts only so long as victory remains possible. When defeat arrives, the crowd disperses quickly. Its catharsis is powerful but conditional.

### Artistic Crowds: The Most Complex Collective Experience

Artistic crowds differ from both political and sports crowds. Audiences in concert halls, cinemas, galleries encounter the same work individually through their own sensibilities. Yet these deeply personal experiences occur simultaneously in shared space.

This coexistence of individuality and collectivity creates the strange beauty of artistic crowds.

At a piano recital, every listener experiences different emotions. Yet applause unites everyone for a fleeting moment. Each person has been moved differently, but the experience of being moved itself becomes communal.

That is the catharsis unique to artistic crowds.
